    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Feeling overwhelmed can definitely affect how you manage your diabetes, but it's important not to adjust your insulin dose without accurate data and medical advice. If your sensor isn't working properly, don't rely solely on it, and definitely don't take an extra insulin dose. Physical activity can affect your blood sugar levels, and your response to insulin might change with varying activity levels, but giving yourself extra insulin could lead to hypoglycemia, which can be dangerous.\n\nUse your insulin pen's backup calculation if available, or once you can, check your blood sugar with a glucometer to understand your current levels accurately. It's crucial to report the malfunctioning sensor to your healthcare team immediately so it can be serviced. In the meantime, to address very high sugar levels, ensure you stay hydrated by drinking water and have some carbohydrates, but only take any corrective action based on a confirmed blood sugar reading and in line with your doctor's advice. Don't hesitate to reach out to your medical team, they can give you real-time advice on how to proceed.",
